            <p>West Phila	December 21. 1888.<lb/>
                Rev S. Morais&#44; LL. D.<lb/></p>
            <p>Esteemed and learned sir&#44;<lb/> You will perhaps be surprised at recei&#45;<lb/>ving a letter from me&#59; but as I have<lb/> written it with the most honorable<lb/> motives&#44; I trust I may expect your<lb/> pardon.  However&#44; I every reason to con&#45;<lb/>clude that you a true teacher in<lb/> Israel&#44; whose tender sensibility of soul&#44;<lb/> which easily interests itself in the joys<lb/> and sorrows of other men will not be<lb/> offended at the recital of my present<lb/> sufferings.  As you are aware&#44; I am<lb/> engaged in teaching both the ancient and<lb/> modern languages&#44; and although<lb/> my compensation is not very great&#44; I<lb/> have managed to make both ends<lb/> meet.  As I am now 62 years of<lb/> age and not very strong&#44;&#45;&#45;I took<lb/> a very heavy cold on the 21 of Nov<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>last&#44; and I suffered the most <sic>excru&#45;<lb/>ating</sic> pain&#44; that the Physician had<lb/> to use instruments on several occas&#45;<lb/>ions to relieve me&#44; but thanks to &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> the Physician of Israel I am<lb/> improving rapidly&#44; but I am forbid&#45;<lb/>den by the Dr to leave the room<lb/> for a few days&#44; as the weather may<lb/> not be suitable and take a<lb/> relapse.  I am at present in great<lb/> need of nourishment&#44; and I am<lb/> almost distracted&#44; not knowing how<lb/> to be relieved from its awful pressure.<lb/>  Thus circumstanced&#44; I have taken the<lb/> liberty to ask you Rev Sir&#44; for the<lb/> loan of one or two dollars&#44; and you<lb/> may be assured&#44; that in a few weeks<lb/> I shall be able to repay it.  The bearer<lb/> is one of my scholars&#44; and you can<lb/> send that amount by him.  I am con&#45;<lb/>fident that you will not think less<lb/> of me on account of my present distress<lb/> Very Respectfully<lb/> S. Lazarus.<lb/></p>
            </body>
